Optimization over the space of probability measures is not only widely applicable, but also offers a useful perspective for analyzing certain complicated finite-dimensional nonconvex optimization problems. In particular, lifting such problems to optimization problems over probability measures can lead to better structural properties, such as convexity. Mean-field Langevin dynamics provides a representative example of this idea. Its central motivation is that some highly nonconvex optimization problems arising in neural network training become better behaved when reformulated as the optimization of a functional on the space of probability measures. This viewpoint also makes it possible to build a theoretical foundation for understanding the convergence of SGD. In what follows, we briefly introduce this perspective, mainly based on the paper by [Hu, Kaitong, et al]. The main analytical framework of this theory can be illustrated by Figure 2. Motivation: Neural NetworksSuppose we have datasets $(z_m,y_m)_{m=1}^N$, where $z_m\in \mathbb{R}^{l_0}$ is the data and $y_m\in \mathbb{R}^{l_L}$ is the corresponding label. The aim of the neural network is to reconstruct the map from all $z_m$ to $y_m$. Let $\varphi:\mathbb{R}	o\mathbb{R}$ be a nonlinear activation function and $\varphi^l:\mathbb{R}^l	o\mathbb{R}^l$ be pointwise, that is$$\varphi^l(z)=(\varphi(z_1),\varphi(z_2),\cdots,\varphi(z_l))\quad 	ext{for } z=(z_1,z_2,\cdots,z_l).$$Then the framework for neural neural network is shown as follows. Figure 1: The framework for neural neural network. The parameters we need to optimize can be listed as$$\Psi=\left((\alpha^1, eta^1),(\alpha^2, eta^2),\cdots,(\alpha^L, eta^L)ight)\in \Pi=\left((\mathbb{R}^{l_1	imes l_0}	imes \mathbb{R}^{l_1})	imes (\mathbb{R}^{l_2	imes l_1}	imes \mathbb{R}^{l_2})	imes \cdots 	imes (\mathbb{R}^{l_L	imes l_{L-1}}	imes \mathbb{R}^{l_L})ight).$$And the reconstruction map can be defined as$$ egin{aligned}\operatorname{R\Psi}: \mathbb{R}^{l_0}&amp;	o \mathbb{R}^{l_L}\\z^0&amp;\mapsto z^L.\end{aligned}$$And the learning task can be formulated as the following optimization problem (often non-convex)$$\inf_{\Psi\in\Pi} \int_{\mathbb{R}^{l_0}	imes \mathbb{R}^{l_L}} \Phi\Big(y-(\operatorname{R\Psi})(z)\Big)\ 
u(dz,dy),$$where $\Phi: \mathbb{R}^{l_L}	o \mathbb{R}$ is a convex function. Two Layer Neural NetworksNow we focus on the two layer neural networks. Let $l_0=d-1,L=2, l_1=n, l_2=1$ and $ eta^1= eta^2=0$. We can partition the matrix $\alpha^1\in \mathbb{R}^{n	imes (d-1)}$ into blocks$$\alpha^1= egin{pmatrix}(\alpha_1^1)^T\\(\alpha_2^1)^T\\vdots\\(\alpha_n^1)^T\end{pmatrix},\quad \alpha_i^1\in \mathbb{R}^{d-1},\ i=1,2,\cdots,n$$and let$$\alpha^2=\Big( rac{c_1}{n}, rac{c_2}{n},\cdots, rac{c_n}{n}\Big),\quad c_i\in \mathbb{R},\ i=1,2,\cdots,n.$$Then for input $z^0\in \mathbb{R}^{d-1}$, we have$$z^1=\varphi^n(\alpha^1 z^0)= egin{pmatrix}\varphi(\alpha_1^1\cdot z^0)\\varphi(\alpha_2^1\cdot z^0)\\vdots\\varphi(\alpha_n^1\cdot z^0)\end{pmatrix}$$and$$z^2=\alpha^2z^1= rac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n c_i\varphi(\alpha_i^1\cdot z^0),$$where ‚Äú$\cdot$‚ÄĚ denotes the inner product. Hence the reconstruction map for two layer neural networks problem is$$ egin{aligned}\operatorname{R\Psi}: \mathbb{R}^{d-1}&amp;	o \mathbb{R}\\z&amp;\mapsto  rac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n c_i\varphi(\alpha_i^1\cdot z).\end{aligned}$$Then the learning task can be formulated as the following optimization problem (often non-convex)$$\inf_{\alpha_i,\ c_i,\ i=1,2,\cdots,n} \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \Phi\Big(y- rac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n c_i\varphi(\alpha_i\cdot z)\Big)\ 
u(dz,dy),$$where $\Phi: \mathbb{R}	o \mathbb{R}$ is a convex function. To simplify the notations, we denote $x=(\alpha,c)\in \mathbb{R}^{d}$ and$$\widehat\varphi (x,z):= c\varphi(\alpha\cdot z).$$Then the optimization problem can be written as$$\inf_{x^i=(\alpha_i,c_i),\ i=1,2,\cdots,n} F^n(x^1,\cdots,x^n):= \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \Phi\Big(y- rac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n \widehat\varphi(x^i,z)\Big)\ 
u(dz,dy).	ag{P1}$$One of the most important observation is that if we lift the finite-dimensional optimization problem (P1) to the infinite-dimensional optimization problem over the space of probability measures (P2), it will become convex.$$\inf_{m\in \mathcal{P}(\mathbb{R}^d)} F(m):=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \Phi\Big(y-\mathbb{E}_{X\sim m}[\widehat\varphi(X,z)]\Big)\ 
u(dz,dy).	ag{P2}$$ Proposition 1. The functional $F: \mathcal{P}(\mathbb{R}^d)	o\mathbb{R}$ is convex. Proof : For all $m,m^\prime\in \mathcal{P}(\mathbb{R}^d)$ and all $t\in [0,1]$, $$ egin{aligned}F((1-t)m+tm^\prime) &amp;=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \Phi\Big(y-\mathbb E_{X\sim (1-t)m+tm^\prime}[\widehat\varphi(X,z)]\Big)\ 
u(dz,dy)\\&amp;=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \Phi\Big((1-t)(y-\mathbb E_{X\sim m}[\widehat\varphi(X,z)])+t(y-\mathbb E_{X\sim m^\prime}[\widehat\varphi(X,z)])\Big)\ 
u(dz,dy)\\&amp;\le (1-t)\int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \Phi\Big(y-\mathbb E_{X\sim m}[\widehat\varphi(X,z)]\Big)\ 
u(dz,dy)+t \int_{\mathbb{R}^{d}} \Phi\Big(y-\mathbb E_{X\sim m^\prime}[\widehat\varphi(X,z)]\Big)\ 
u(dz,dy)\\&amp;=(1-t)F(m)+tF(m^\prime).\end{aligned}$$ Hence $F$ is convex. $\square$ Now maybe you want to ask what is the relationship between (P1) and (P2) ? It is obvious that$$F^n(x^1,\cdots,x^n)=F( rac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n \delta_{x^i}).$$Hence we have$$\inf_{x^i,\ i=1,2,\cdots,n} F^n(x^1,\cdots,x^n)\ge \inf_{m\in \mathcal{P}(\mathbb{R}^d)} F(m).$$Moreover,we have the following theorem, which shows that the infimum of (P1) and (P2) is very close as long as $n$ is sufficiently large. Theorem 1. We assume that the 2nd order linear functional derivative of $F$ exists, is jointly continuous in both variables and that there is $L&gt;0$ such that for any random variables $\eta_1,\eta_2$ such that $\mathbb{E}[|\eta_i|^2]&lt;\infty$, $i=1,2$, it holds that $$\mathbb{E} \left[\sup_{
