abla\left( rac{\delta F}{\delta m}(m,x)ight).$$ However, even under the Assumption 1, the existence and uniqueness of the minimizer of the optimization problem (P2) is not clear. So instead, we can consider the regularized problem (P3). $$\inf_{m\in \mathcal{P}(\mathbb{R}^d)} V^\sigma(m):=F(m)+ rac{\sigma^2}{2}H(m),	ag{P3}$$where$$g(x)=e^{-U(x)} 	ext{ with } U 	ext{ s.t. } \int_{\mathbb{R}^d} e^{-U(x)}dx=1,$$is the density of the Gibbs measure and the function $U$ satisfies the following conditions. Assumption 2. The function $U:\mathbb{R}^d 	o \mathbb{R}$ belongs to $C^\infty$. Further, (i) there exist constants $C_U&gt;0$ and $C‚Äô_U\in\mathbb{R}$ such that$$
